title Mantra's own apply step lands; a bolt written is not a bolt visible
prompt Keaton said "approve your recommendation either way" to the fork named at the end of the last turn (Mantra's apply step vs. the deterministic-simulation horizon). Chose Mantra's apply step -- the same proven pattern applied to a sibling module, mechanical and lower-risk than opening a genuinely new capability.
think read mantra/recall_lap1.rye closely before writing anything, since its own doc comment names a real standing rule for the whole family: every file after the foundation imports it and edits nothing beneath itself. This meant the right shape was a new composing file, not an edit to append_leaf itself -- the same discipline neth_apply_step.rye already modeled for Neth (compose on the already-witnessed primitive, do not touch it).
think designed bolt_apply_step.rye around one honest seam: write_leaf_pending copies a leaf's fields into a pending slot this module owns, touching the real BoltCatalog not at all; apply_pending is the one and only path that ever calls the foundation's own append_leaf. This means apply_pending adds zero new admission rules -- any refusal (RevisionImmutable, RevisionOutOfOrder, CatalogFull, Overflow) is append_leaf's own, forwarded unmodified, which is a stronger, more honest claim than reimplementing those checks a second time would have been.
think built and ran the witness directly against the real recall_lap1 surface rather than an internal flag standing in for it -- first run failed with an assertion I had gotten wrong about recall()'s own contract: recall() returns a normal RecallResult with outcome .never for an unbound name, it does not throw PathNotBound (that error path is reserved for a genuinely inconsistent state -- resolve_binding says .here but find_leaf can't find it, which should never happen in practice). Read recall_lap1.rye's own recall() function line by line to find the real contract rather than guessing a second time, then corrected the witness to check outcome == .never and len == 0, which is what the real function actually promises.
think this is the value of running these witnesses in the same sitting they are written, on this now-raised cloud sandbox: the wrong assumption about recall()'s contract was caught and fixed in under a minute, rather than shipping a witness that would have needed a host-run handoff to discover the same mistake.
think chose the crash-in-the-window test to reuse the catalog's own real semantics rather than inventing a parallel state: revision 2's pending write, discarded by a crash, leaves resolve_binding(revision 2) reporting .not_yet -- which is recall_lap1's own honest answer for "the next slot in order, not yet admitted," proving the crash-safety claim through the real namespace law rather than a bespoke flag.
obs three sibling patterns now stand real-GREEN across two modules this session (Neth's two-posture root install, Neth's apply step, Mantra's apply step) -- the last one composing cleanly on an existing, unedited foundation, which is itself evidence the family's own edits-nothing-beneath-itself rule is doing real work rather than being a merely aspirational label.
file mantra/bolt_apply_step.rye -- new; write_leaf_pending/apply_pending/recover_after_crash, composing on recall_lap1.BoltCatalog without editing it
file mantra/bolt_apply_step_witness.rye -- new; five claims against the real recall()/resolve_binding contract, corrected once after a first run caught a wrong assumption about that contract
file tools/mantra_bolt_apply_step_witness.rish -- new; build+run+assert wrapper matching the existing Neth witness shape
file tools/parity_ch01.rish -- wired the new witness into the living suite, directly after the Neth apply-step entry
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md -- Mantra apply step marked landed and confirmed GREEN
